 response to injury we do n't know yet , '' said Dr. Jesse Roth , geriatrician-in-chief of the North Shore Long Island Jewish Health System , who has studied insulin 's role in the brain since the 1980s .", "Last year , in a study of brain samples from 45 Alzheimer 's patients , de la Monte found that the number of insulin receptors in the frontal cortex , the center of intellect , drops by 80 percent in advanced cases of the disease , meaning that the cells do n't get the insulin they need to survive .", 'If the insulin researchers are right , those problems could be secondary to a more fundamental breakdown in the way brain cells process insulin to generate energy and protect themselves against death .', "In recent years , De la Monte 's lab has shown that the brain actually produces insulin itself rather than relying on insulin from the pancreas that circulates in the rest of the body ."]}, {'file_name': 'NYT_ENG_20060130.0088', 'file_top_sent': ['Freeman and her analyst saw unexplored childhood and adult fears as the cause of mental illness -- even of psychotic conditions like schizophrenia .', "It was these advances that Freeman relentlessly publicized as The Times ' reporter on mental health .", "Freeman 's efforts recall a heady time in the history of psychiatry , when two competing groups , the followers of Sigmund Freud and those who favored physical manipulation of the brain , each believed it had found a `` cure '' for mental illness .", 'Meanwhile , the grand claims made by Freeman and others for psychoanalysis have been challenged .', "As a reporter for The New York Times in the 1940s and '50s , she worked to remove the stigma of mental illness , even writing a revealing book that chronicled her own psychoanalysis ."]}, {'file_name': 'XIN_ENG_20051117.0403', 'file_top_sent': ["`` Our insights into the important role that the proteins PDE4B and DISC1 may play in the mis-function of the brain that leads to schizophrenia will lead our thinking in the devel